      "objectEndDate": 1699,
      "medium": "porcelain with overglaze color enamel and gold decoration (Hizen ware; Kakiemon type)",
      "description": "This kakiemon-type jar with plum design is a product made for the European markets. Here, Japanese kakiemon potters transformed the typical plum, bamboo, and pine motifs into a theme appreciating the plum. The 9th-century Japanese scholar and politician Sugawara Michizane established the plum as a symbol of scholarship. An excellent poet, particularly of Chinese-style poetry, he was also well known for his love of plum blossoms. Later, the plum came to represent tenmangu, a shrine for Sugawara.",
      "objectURL": "https://clevelandart.org/art/1964.273",
